5.3 Theoretical Analysis
5.3.1 New Explanation Objective. From previous discussions, it is shown that Gâ€² obtained via Equation 1 cannot be safely used as
explanations. One main drawback of existing GNN explanation
methods lies in the inductive bias that the same outcomes do not
guarantee the same causes, leaving existing approaches vulnerable
towards spurious explanations. An illustration is given in Figure 3.
Objective proposed in Equation 1 optimizes the mutual information between explanation candidate Gâ€² and ğ‘ŒË† , corresponding to maximize the overlapping between ğ» (Gâ€²) and ğ» (ğ‘ŒË† ) in Figure 3(a), or region ğ‘†1 âˆª ğ‘†2 in Figure 3(b). Here, ğ» denotes information entropy. However, this learning target cannot prevent the danger of generating spurious explanations. Provided Gâ€² may fall into the region ğ‘†2, which cannot faithfully represent graph G. Instead, a more sensible
objective should be maximizing region ğ‘†1 in Figure 3(b). The intuition behind this is that in the search input space that causes the same outcome, identified Gâ€² should account for both representative and discriminative parts of original G, to prevent spurious expla-
nations that produce the same outcomes due to different causes. Concretely, finding Gâ€² that maximize ğ‘†1 can be formalized as:

